; branch-choice-order.form — learned ordering for BMF/Form choice branches.
;
; THE ASK:
;   Choice should not stay fixed in source order forever. A parser, route, or
;   scheduler can remember which alternatives recently succeeded or failed,
;   keep older evidence as stable memory, and order the next run from that
;   witnessed history.
;
; THE SHAPE  (runnable: form-stdlib/branch-choice-order.fk · proven:
; tests/branch-choice-order-band.fk -> 511)
;
;   A candidate is `(path short-success short-fail long-success long-fail
;   alignment trust)`.
;
;   1. SHORT MEMORY reacts fast. Recent success is weighted higher than long
;      success, so a fresh winning branch can outrank a historically good
;      branch that is now failing.
;   2. LONG MEMORY keeps the body from thrashing. Older successes and failures
;      continue to count after the short window is rolled forward.
;   3. CORE GATES stay separate. Alignment and trust can gate a candidate even
;      when branch feedback is hot, so "it often works" does not become "it is
;      coherent to do."
;   4. ROLL-FORWARD moves short stats into long stats once a threshold is
;      reached, then clears the short window. No mutation is needed; the next
;      candidate record is a returned value.
;   5. TWO LANES remain available: `bco-choose-best` for learned ordering and
;      `bco-choose-any` for the cheap unordered lane.
;   6. RECEIPTS BECOME LEARNING DATA through `choice-receipt-learning.fk`:
;      a selected success increments short success, a selected fail increments
;      short fail, silence and unselected branches stay unchanged. The adapter
;      is proven by `tests/choice-receipt-learning-band.fk` -> 255.
;
; WHY THIS IS THE KERNEL-SIDE CONTRACT:
;   It mirrors the proven branch-prediction lesson without importing hardware
;   machinery wholesale: local recency adapts quickly, long history stabilizes,
;   and a selector compares integer counters instead of floating ratios. The
;   open question for the runtime is carrier policy: where receipts are stored,
;   how wide the short window should be per grammar, and when exploration should
;   deliberately try a lower-scoring alternative.
;
; KIN:
;   choice-receipt.fk (what happened) · choice-receipt-learning.fk (what the
;   receipt changes) · online-accuracy.fk (success/fail counts) ·
;   sequence-predictor.fk (history as the model) · recognition-router.fk
;   (most-data wins, silence when no claim earns trust) · confidence-calibrate.fk
;   (scores become comparable before routing).
